evidence that it creates significant roadblocks to sustainability
through increasing resource constraints (i.e., peak oil, water limitations)
and sink constraints (i.e., climate disruption). Overcoming these
roadblocks and creating a sustainable and desirable future will require
an integrated, systems level redesign of our socio-ecological regime
focused explicitly and directly on the goal of sustainable quality
of life rather than the proxy of unlimited material growth. This
transition, like all cultural transitions, will occur through an
evolutionary process, but one that we, to a certain extent, can control
and direct. We suggest an integrated set of worldviews, institutions,
and technologies to stimulate and seed this evolutionary redesign
of the current socio-ecological regime to achieve global sustainability.},
